      ],
      "source": "https://tocny.org/town-history/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "An 1893 map shows five railroad stations strung across central Cheektowaga, marking the town’s early rail hub.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://tocny.org/town-history/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Cheektowaga was first settled in 1808 by Appollos Hitchcock, who built a log cabin near present‑day Borden and Broadway.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12,
        29
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2",
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.britannica.com/place/Cheektowaga"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "For almost a century, the area remained hunting and fishing grounds of the Six Nations before European settlement.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://tocny.org/town-history/"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Ga‑sko‑sa‑da, or Falls Village, once stretched along the north bank of Cayuga Creek, with long houses built from Borden Road to Union Road.",
